<item>
            <title>[DAEMON-163] __apxMultiSzToJvmOptions has odd use of IS_INVALID_HANDLE</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DAEMON-163</link>
                <project id="12310468" key="DAEMON">Commons Daemon</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;__apxMultiSzToJvmOptions has odd use of IS_INVALID_HANDLE:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;if&lt;/span&gt; (IS_INVALID_HANDLE(hPool))
    buff = apxPoolAlloc(hPool, (n + 1) * sizeof(JavaVMOption) + (l + 1));
&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;else&lt;/span&gt;
    buff = apxAlloc((n + 1) * sizeof(JavaVMOption) + (l + 1));
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The condition appears to be the wrong way round.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, the method apxPoolAlloc also checks for IS_INVALID_HANDLE, and if true, the code resolves to calling&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;__apxPoolAllocCore(_st_sys_pool, dwSize, 0)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;which is exactly what apxAlloc() does. As far as I can tell, the hPool parameter is never used here. &lt;br/&gt;
If that is the intention, then just keep the code in the else part of the statement.&lt;br/&gt;
If not, then just keep the code in the if part of the statement.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
